{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559484/1949063001/0244.xml":{"full_text":"THE MARION PROGRESS\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY BY THE\nMcdowell publishing co.\nMARION, N. C.\nTELEPHONE 64\nS. E. WHITTEN, Editor and Proprietor\nEntered at the Posfbffice at Marion, N. C.,\nas second class matter\nSUBSCRIPTION RATE\nOne year $2.00\nStrictly in Advance\n1 >niwW \"l\n\"'North Carolina\n'WtlSS ASSOCIATION $1\nJULY FOURTH, 1949\nJuly Fourth, the anniversary of the historic\nDeclaration of Independence, will be observed\nin every American state. There will be speech\nes, programs and various celebrations as the\nmen and women of today eulogize the great\nevent of 1776.\nMillions of people, including thousands in\nMcDowell county, will turn a reverent gaze in\nthe direction of the early heroes of this repub\nlic, the men who .placed their lives and fortun\nes in hostage for the freedom of the thirteen\ncolonies. These early patriots did not then\nprehend the full nature of the nation that\nwould spread to the Pacific and cast its line\nacross the oceans.\nIt is well, no doubt, for us to celebrate the\nday with pageantry and pomp, but it is better\nwe think, for us, as individuals, to dedicate\nourselves to the principles upon which the re\npublic was founded. Before we can fully ac\ncomplish this realty, it is necessary to thor\noughly understand the fundamental princi\nples of American republicanism and to resolve\nthat, as citizens of a great nation, we will loy\nally support them.\nThe allegiance of the heart and mind is\nworth more tp the country than physical parti\ncipation in any public display. At best, pomp\nand ceremony can only offer a spectacle to this\ngeneration but complete obedience to the vit\nal truths of democracy will serve as an accept\nable offering to those who come after us. Let\nus remember that this republic will survive\nthrough the genuine loyalty of its men and\nwomen, not by virtue of parades, processions,\naddresses and poppycock sententiously spon\nsored by pomporas individuals.\nIt should be recognized that a few men liv\ning in 1776 had any idea that the union of the\nthirteen colonies, modestly referred to as these\nUnited States, would develop into the present\nhighly centralized government. Few then\ndreamed that the federal government would\nbecome so all-powerful as to dwarf the respec\ntive states or that the rights of the people\nwould depend upon the action of the so-called\nconfederation.\nWe will not prolong this article with an expo\nsition of the citizen's duties in connection with\nthe American ideal of government. These\nwould vary with individuals. We merely sug-j\ngest to every man, woman and child, who hap\npens to read this article, that each for himself\nor herself undertake to understand the prin\nciples of a republican form of government and\nthat each, as a loyal American, pledge anew a\npersonal faith in the strength and permanency\nof our country.\nSuch a resolution, engraved in the hearts of\nmillions of citizens, will be the greatest pos\nsible commemoration of a rightfully celebrat\ned anniversary. It will be worth more than all\nthe public performances, staged in the name of j\nliberty, since the advent of the human race.\nTALK MAY BE OF PEACE\nWhile hopeful that some modus vivendi can\nbe arranged with the Russians and somewhat\nencouraged by reports that Moscow is think\ning along the lines of rapprochment, we call\nyour attention to the recent declaration of Er\nnest Bevin, British Foreign Secretary, that\nRussia has the largest army in the world.\nThis is a fact to be duly considered in con\nnection with all talk about peace. As Mr. Bevin\npoints out dictators talk peace when preparing\nfor war. This may be the case with the Rus\nsians, and then again it may be an unjust sus\npicion.\nWho knows? We do not. Neither do the re\nsponsible heads of the democratic nations of\nthe world. Consequently, while anxious for a\npeace that will lead to large-scale world devel\nopment they must be prepared for whatever\nthe future brings.\nThe memories of men are short. After the\nfirst World War there was the Pact of Paris,\ndesigned to outlaw war, and the Nine Power\nTreaty about China, designed to prevent ag\ngression in the Far East. These documents\nwere carefully drawn and duly executed. A\ngreat many people were positive that they end\ned, the necessity for preparedness.\n\nBE ALIVE ON THE FIFTH\nHundreds of people are killed every year\nby accidents during the Fourth of July holi\nday.\nThat plain fact, is borne out year after year\nby figures from the National Safety Council.\nWhy are they killed?\nIt is easy to advance a lot of deeply philoso\nphical reasons. The hurry-up world we live in.\nThe adventurous, take-a-chance American\nspirit. The animalistic discourtesy of man to\nman.\nBut there is no need to do any heavy think\ning on the reasons for the. holiday death toll.\nThe reasons are quite simple, really.\nFor one thing, more people are driving au\ntomobiles. When more cars are on the road and\nthey are traveling farther, the chances for ac\ncident go up proportionately.\nPleasure-bent drivers usually are in a hurry.\nThey want to get somewhere to start having\nfun, or they are pounding along on the first\nleg of a summer vacation trip. A lot of people\nare doing the same thing, and it becomes a\nsort of race. Driving too fast, passing when the\nview is obstructed, following other cars too\nclosely\u2014all seem important in the senseless\n1 race to save a minute.\nBeaches are crowded, too. A lot of occasion\nal swimmers overestimate their skill or their\nendurance. Children excited by holiday fever\nelude adult supervision. Amateur boat hand\nlers find that small boats require a practiced\nhand and prudent conduct.\nDuring this holiday, some parents permit\ntheir children to play with fire and explosives\nthat on any other day would bring swift and\ncertain rebuke. Even adults, not satisfied with\nthe machine gun splatter of firecrackers, have\nbeen known to rig up lethal concoctions of dy\nnamite.\nThe tonic of celebration leads to excesses in\nexercise, eating, exposure to sun.\nAll these things contribute to Fourth of July\ndeaths. And it would be simple to prevent such\naccidents.\nDon't take a trip just to be going somewhere.\nThere are many delights near home. Drive\nslower. Don't become impatient at unimpor\ntant delays. Be courteous to other drivers and\npedestrians.\nBe temperate in your swimming. Keep an\nalert eye on children. Take your family to a\npublic fireworks display instead of risking\ntragedy by personal handling of explosives.\nThese are the simple things that will ensure\ndelight in a summer holiday\u2014that will bring\nyou home relaxed and refreshed, that will see\nyour children safely in bed to dream of the\nday's pleasure. These are the simple things\nthat will make this Fourth of July mean joy\ninstead of tragedy.\nKipling said it: \"Teach us delight in simple\nthings and mirth that has no bitter springs.\"\nTHE ROAD TO STATISM\nThe whole American public should harken\nto the warning sounded by James F. Byrnes in\nhis address to the graduating class of Wash\nington and Lee University that this country is\ntraveling down the road to statism.\nHe was not exaggerating when he said that\n\"if some of the new programs seriously pro-;\nposed should be adopted, there is danger that\nthe individual, whether farmer, worker, man\nufacturer, lawyer, or doctor\u2014will soon be an'\neconomic slave pulling an oar in the galley of\nthe state.\"\nThe danger is in the psychology of the peo\nple. Little by little they have been granting\nmore and more authority to the Federal gov\nernment, its -bureaus, and its department\nheads, until it is taking to itself subtly and al\nmost imperceptibly, powers that the Consti\ntution never intended that it should have. j\nThe people by their votes are electing re\npresentatives who in turn vote these powers\nto the Federal government in order to get\nmore Federal money for their districts. The!\nFederal money, then, is being held out as bait J\nto the people to persuade them to give up their\nliberties for material gain.\nThe original purpose of our government was\nto protect our liberties. Its present purpose, if\nthe planners have their way, will be to sup\nport all of us from the cradle to the grave.\nThese planners look upon the government,\nnot as a protection for the citizens' rights, but\nas an instrument for a planned economy.\nEvery time we give more of those powers to\nthe Federal government we give away some\nof our liberties, and let us not fool ourselves\nthat we don't.\nSocial security is costing us the right to man\nage our own property\u2014that is our wages. The\nBrannan plan will regiment the farmer. The\nproposed economic expansion act will put the\ngovernment into competiton with private busi\nness and will surround business with all kinds\nof controls.\u2014The Charlotte Observer.\nDrive more carefully than ever and thus\nmake doubly sure the safety of your own life.\nOUR DEMOCRACY -byM.t\nLinn limn \u25a0lUnuiiiBi.iiuiu.iiiiiiLii.iinnim imnin III III. HI HU iJIU WKMTTimCn\nvjflfie oj (6 wai> an a^puratiovi. cDocLuj it is an\naccoyn^fi&hment.C(f{ow i>i iJ a ie lite eeiomi urfiicfi\nvoe sougjair and icon. 16 &est appreciated Ei^i^iose uj}1a\nfaaue comejaom otnet fancL to .i/iate i&em.\nNEWS NOTES\nHOMER FREES 4 JAILBIRDS\nPlymouth, Mass.\u2014A home run\n\"drove\" four prisoners out of the\nPlymouth House of Correction dur\ning a recent softball game. When\nthe guard opened the gate to re\ntrieve a ball that had been banged\nover the fence by a player, the\nprisoners dashed out. The guard\ncouldn't stop them because he was\nnot armed, in accordance with a\nruling in force since the killing of a\nprisoner in an attempted break sev\neral years ago.\nOCTUPUS CUDDLES GIN\nSydney, Australia.\u2014An octupus\nwhich two fishermen drew up at\nthe end of their line was cuddling\na full bottle of gin. The fishermen\nthrew the octupus back into tjje\nwater. It's your guess as to what\nhappened to the gin.\nONLY GRADUATE\nAda, Kansas.\u2014\"Eva Mae Brad\nbury, 16, recently graduated from\nhigh school, the only graduate. She\nhas been a one-student class since\nshe started in the first grade.\nISLAND UP AND DOWN\nHonolulu.\u2014Falcon Island has\ndisappeart i for the fourth time in\nits recorded history and a man,\nwho ought to know, says it will rise\nagain some day, bigger and better\nthan ever. The island is (or was)\na small, volcanic member of the\nTonga group, located 2,600 miles\nsouthwest of Hawaii.\nQUIT SMOKING\nGets $19,320\nBrisbane, Australia.\u2014Deciding to\ngive up smoking tobacco, Norman\nPayne sold his tobacco, papers and\ncigarettes to a friend, and, \u00abwith\nthe proceeds, bought a ticket in a\nlottery in Brisbane. It was the win\nning ticket, bringing Payne $19,\n320.\nTHUMB 1,616 MILES\nMobile, Ala.\u2014Mrs. Hattie E.\nThompson, 54-year-old grandmoth\ner, and Mrs. Pearl Emney, 52, of\nOttawa, fulfilled a life long ambi\ntion to take a hitch-hiking trip by\nthumbing their way from Ottawa\nto Mobile, a distance of 1,616 miles,\nto visit a brother, W. W. Mackie, of\nnearby Theodore. They hadn't seen\neach other in 47 years. The trip\ntook five days and cost them a total\nof $11.75. They plan to make the\ntrip home the same way\u2014via the\nthumbing route.\nVET HELPS ANOTHER VET\nChicago.\u2014Saving up $1,000 for\na down payment on a house, Lar\nry Borko, and his wife, Anna, learn\ned that the VA would not make a\nloan on the house unless it was\npainted. Borko, a handless veteran,\ncould not afford to have the paint\ning done or do it himself, having\nlost his hands as a Seabee on Oki\nnawa when a Japanese mine explod\ned in front of him. Hearing of his\nplight, however, Legionnaires, who\nwere painters, twenty-five strong,\nbearing brushes and buckets of\npaint, swarmed over the house and\nput on one coat. They promised to\nreturn a week later to put on the\nsecond and do the trimming.\nWAS HIS FACE RED?\nFrederick, Okla.\u2014 When the\ntornado siren began wailing during\nthe night, Dan Largin sleepily dis\ncarded his pajamas and groped for\nhis clothing before making a dash\nfor the storm cellar. He didn't find\nthem, but took comfort in the fact\nthat only the family was in the\ncellar and thei-e were no lights. As\nhe settled down, however, in rush\ned some neighbors\u2014with a light.\nSOME SALESMAN!\nLos Angeles.\u2014Stopped by a traf\nfic officer for driving through a\npedestrian cross walk, Bill Carmi\nchael, an insurance agent, began\ntalking to the officer. After a few\nminutes of conversation, Carmichael\nwalked away with the officer's ap\nplication for an insurance policy.\n\"DEAD END KID\"\nNOW DOCTOR\nAugusta, Ga.\u2014Remember Milty\nthe fat boy of the original \"Dead\nEnd Kids?\" Well, he's a doctor now.\nMilty, who is Bernard Puasley, of\nBerkeley, Cal. in real life, got his\ndiploma from the University of\nGeorgia's School of Medicine in Au- i\ngusta, on June 8.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nAccording to some experts, the\ncurrent business decline is about\nhalf over and, by fall, an upturn in\nbusiness is expected. The output of\ngoods is down by about 10 per cent\nand wholesale prices are down 8\nper cent. Consumer buying is hold\ning up fairly well, while business\nbuyers are holding up, waiting for\nprices to decline further. j\nFirst members from North Caro\nlina to the House of Representatives\nof the United States since the adop\ntion of the Constitution were John\nB. Ashe, Timothy Bloodworth. Wil-;\nliam Shadwick, John Steele and\nHugh Williamson.\n200,000 forest fires last\nyear\u2014a major disaster for\nyour country. And\u2014facts\nprove this\u201490% of these\nfires were man-caused\nstarted by people like you\nand your neighbor.\nPlease be careful!\nyou can\nPREVENT FOREST FIRES!\nQ,\nTALL TALES\nBy ELIZABETH WHITTEN\n\nThis morning I was writing a few\nitems about people going to beach\nes and people paving summer guests,\netc. When I looked up I saw a couple\ncoming in. The man had on a new,\nblue gray suit with the creases in\nthe trousers pressed to a fine line,\nhis hair was slicked down and his\nshoes a high shine. The girl was\nwearing a pretty blue eyelet dress\nwith white accessories, white hat\nand gloves and a pink carnation\ncorsage.\nOh, goody, a wedding, I thought.\nBut they just wanted to buy a sheet\nof white cardboard, they said. All\nthe time I was wrapping it up I\nthought maybe they were just get\nting their nerves settled before\nlaunching into the story of their\nmarriage.\n\"Now,\" the girl said, \"we want\na package of colored chalk.\"\n\"I'm sorry, we don't have that,\"\nI said. And then, as they turned to\nleave I couldn't keep rny curiosity\nany longer, I said, \"I thought you\nwere coming to tell me you'd just\nbeen married.\"\nOh, no, the man smiled with a\nwicked gleam in his eye. \"We came\nnp here with a couple to be married\nand we're fixing to put a sign on\ntheir car JUST MARRIED.\nI let them use one of the colored\npencils we use to mark advertising.\nThey wanted to know if I had two\npencils so they could mark it fast\ner and heavier. I didn't, but they\nworked harder than if they were\ngetting paid for it 'Snd soon they left\ngrinning from ear to ear. I won\ndered if the bride and bridegroom\nwere any happier than they were.\nAfter all these years I've written\nsocial news, it's still hard to recog\nnize engaged couples. That's the\ngood part of newspaper work\u2014\nsomething new and different all the\ntime.\nOne night I was at home listen\ning to the radio when I heard a\nknock. I opened the front door and\nthere stood a boy and a girl. For\nthe moment I thought they had mis\ntaken my house for the teen-age\ncenter at the community building\nacross the street.\n\"Here we are!\" the girl exclaim\ned jubilantly.\n\"Y-e-s-s\", you are,,\" I said hesi\ntantly, not knowing whether I was\nsupposed to expect them or not.\n\"Won't you come in?\"\nThey did. It seems that several\nweeks before I had asked a member\nof the girl's family if she was get\nting married sobn and had been told\nthey would let me know if she did.\nShe had picked up the threads of\nthe conversation right where it was\nleft.after a lapse of several weeks.\nWe had the write-up well under\nway when there was a second knock.\nI opened the door and a little girl\nabout five years old whisked by me\nwithout a word. Although she had\nnever been in the house before, she\nfound her way into the room where\nthe couple was seated without the\nslightest hesitation. She was the\nbride's sister and was tired of wait\ning in the car.\nAnd one day while I was walking\ndown the street I saw a girl walk\ning beside me. She was looking me\nover very carefully as we strolled\nalong.\nIn a few minutes she stepped di\nrectly in front of me and said, \"are\nyou that woman that goes to all the\nweddings?\" She was planning \"to be\nmarried and wanted to talk to m&\nabout the write-up.\nYou know the answer. But do\nyou know this?: you get mora\nprotection it less cost from\ndividend-paying MUTUAL\nfire policies issued by finan\ncially strong company accf\nserviced by a- capable, expe\nrienced agency; It will pay\nyou to learn why so call\nus for details.\nJ. H. TATE\nPhene 120-X Marion, N. C.","height":"31472","width":"21248"}}
